1380":"1380","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1787":"1787","1313":"1313","1345":"1345","1785":"1785","1356":"1356","Abt 1277":"about 1277","1245":"1245","1321":"1321","1453":"1453","1299":"1299","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Burton upon Trent St Mowden, Derbyshire, England":"Burton upon Trent St Modwen, Derbyshire, England","West Twyford Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom":"Kedleston, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Twyford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places calledTwyford, for example in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Derbyshire,Hampshire, Leicestershire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, and Norfolk, fromOld English <i>twī-</i> ‘double’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Twiford","meanings":["English: variant of   Twyford  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}